<p style="margin-top:1em; margin-bottom:0em; page-break-before:always">
<HR SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B>Wall Street Journal <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">Op-Ed&#151;FINAL</FONT> </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B>Houston CCS Innovation Zone </B></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B>April&nbsp;19, 2021
</B></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">As President Biden convenes the virtual Leaders Summit on Climate later this month, America has a unique opportunity to spearhead a breakthrough
approach to reducing carbon emissions.&nbsp;About 80% of the world&#146;s energy-related carbon emissions come from three critical sectors of the economy: power generation, commercial transportation and industrial manufacturing. Meaningful progress
toward achieving the world&#146;s climate goals requires emission reductions from these sectors.</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">One of the proven technologies available that could play
a major role is carbon capture and storage, or CCS, the process of sequestering industrial emissions and safely storing them permanently underground. CCS also promises the potential to reduce carbon emissions significantly at a cost competitive to
other solutions, especially for the manufacturing sector.</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">For the past three years at ExxonMobil we have been studying the concept of creating multiuser
CCS &#147;hubs&#148; in industrial areas. They would be located near safe geologic storage sites. A CCS Innovation Zone would bring together government incentives and private-sector investment.</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The heavy-industry area of the Houston Ship Channel on the Gulf Coast of Texas is an ideal location to apply this concept. This area houses one of the
country&#146;s largest sources of industrial emissions and is close to the Gulf of Mexico&#146;s vast subsurface storage potential, where the CO2 would be permanently stored in the pore space of the rocks, thousands of feet below the seafloor.</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Based on Energy Department numbers, we estimate there is adequate capacity along the Gulf Coast to store around 500&nbsp;billion metric tons of CO2. We
further estimate that the Houston concept has the potential to store up to 100&nbsp;million metric tons of carbon a year by 2040. The project could help the city of Houston achieve its goal of becoming carbon-neutral by 2050. </P>
</DIV></Center>


<p style="margin-top:1em; margin-bottom:0em; page-break-before:always">
<HR SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The Houston CCS Innovation Zone concept would require the &#147;whole of government&#148; approach to the
climate challenge that President Biden has championed. Based on our experience with projects of this scale, we estimate the approach could generate tens of thousands of new jobs needed to make and install the equipment to capture the CO2 and
transport it via a pipeline for storage. Such a project would also protect thousands of existing jobs in industries seeking to reduce emissions. In short, large-scale CCS would reduce emissions while protecting the economy. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Government&#146;s role would be to put in place a stable regulatory and legal environment and enable CCS to receive private investment and government
incentives directly. Establishing a price on carbon would also provide the market certainty required to enable businesses to generate returns on carbon-reducing investments. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The lessons and knowledge gained in Houston could be applied to other parts of the country with similar industrial concentrations, including the Midwest and
elsewhere along the Gulf Coast.</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">As the world&#146;s leader in CCS, with about 40% of the total anthropogenic CO2 captured to date and multiple CCS
projects underway around the world, ExxonMobil is eager to play our part to advance this promising concept. CCS would bring us closer to the lower-carbon future we all seek.</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Mr.&nbsp;Woods is ExxonMobil&#146;s chairman and CEO. Mr.&nbsp;Blommaert is president of ExxonMobil Low Carbon Solutions. </P>
</DIV></Center>


<p style="margin-top:1em; margin-bottom:0em; page-break-before:always">
<HR SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B><I>Inside ExxonMobil </I></B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B>April&nbsp;19, 2021 </B></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B>ExxonMobil envisions bold new
idea: a Houston Ship Channel CCS Hub </B></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B>A big idea for lower carbon: </B>ExxonMobil&#146;s new Low Carbon Solutions business is thinking big when it
comes to capturing carbon. We have developed a concept that could effectively decarbonize the heavy industry area in and around the Houston Ship Channel with a large-scale carbon capture and storage (CCS) project. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">We are proposing the concept of a CCS Innovation Zone, which would bring together a wide variety of public and private stakeholders to identify and accelerate
funding sources, policy and regulatory requirements, and other needs to enable project success. And we think Houston is an ideal place to do it. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B>Say
what?</B> &#147;A CCS Innovation Zone would bring together government incentives and private-sector investment,&#148; Chairman and CEO Darren Woods and Low Carbon Solutions President Joe Blommaert wrote in an
<FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">op-ed</FONT> published today in The Wall Street Journal. &#147;The heavy-industry area of the Houston Ship Channel on the Gulf Coast of Texas is an ideal location to apply this concept.&#148; </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B>Why start with Houston?</B> Houston is often referred to as the Energy Capital of the World, and a concept like this one could position the city as leading
the way toward a lower-carbon energy future. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Logistically, Houston is a prime location because there are many large, stationary emissions sources, and
it&#146;s near huge geologic formations that could safely sequester CO<SUB STYLE="font-size:85%; vertical-align:bottom">2</SUB> deep underneath the Gulf of Mexico. The U.S. Department of Energy estimates the storage capacity along the U.S. Gulf
Coast is large enough to store about 500&nbsp;billion metric tons of CO<SUB STYLE="font-size:85%; vertical-align:bottom">2</SUB>, safely and permanently. Our estimates suggest this is equivalent to more than 130 years of industrial and power
generation emissions in the U.S., based on 2018 numbers. This concept could help support the City of Houston&#146;s climate ambitions to become a leader in CCS innovation and reduce its greenhouse gas emissions to be carbon neutral by 2050. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The lessons learned in Houston could ultimately be replicated in other areas of the country with similar conditions, such as in the Midwest or elsewhere along
the U.S. Gulf Coast. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B>Put it in context:</B> The concept is potentially game changing for deployment of CCS and could drastically accelerate U.S.
emission-reduction efforts. Early projections indicate that infrastructure could be built to safely capture and permanently store about 50&nbsp;million metric tons of CO<SUB STYLE="font-size:85%; vertical-align:bottom">2</SUB> annually by 2030, and
double that by 2040. Capturing 100&nbsp;million metric tons of CO<SUB STYLE="font-size:85%; vertical-align:bottom">2</SUB> is roughly equivalent to taking 20&nbsp;million cars off the road. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B>Why a CCS Innovation Zone?</B> As the leader in carbon capture and storage, ExxonMobil has studied the concept and feasibility of creating multi-user CCS
&#147;hubs&#148; in major industrial areas that are near safe and available CO<SUB STYLE="font-size:85%; vertical-align:bottom">2</SUB> storage sites. Our assessment has shown a project of this size could significantly reduce emissions at a lower
cost to society than many other widely available technologies. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">As Darren Woods recently presented in his employee forum, experts, including the
International Energy Agency (IEA) and the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC), agree with us that CCS is one of the critical technologies required to meet society&#146;s ambitions of a lower-carbon future. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center">1 </P>

</DIV></Center>


<p style="margin-top:1em; margin-bottom:0em; page-break-before:always">
<HR SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B><I>Inside ExxonMobil </I></B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B>A collaborative effort: </B>This ambitious concept will require the collective support of industry and government, with a combined investment of
$100&nbsp;billion or more. It could also generate tens of thousands of new direct and indirect jobs, while also protecting current ones. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B>Up for the
challenge:</B> This is an enormous challenge, but one ExxonMobil is well-suited and eager to help lead, due to our long history and expertise in capturing CO<SUB STYLE="font-size:85%; vertical-align:bottom">2</SUB>, our experience in subsurface
reservoir management and our proven performance in safely developing and operating large-scale projects. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The Low Carbon Solutions team, whose leadership
now includes President Joe Blommaert, Vice President of Strategy and Advocacy Erik Oswald, and Vice President of Business Development Guy Powell, will be leading ExxonMobil&#146;s efforts to pursue this CCS Innovation Zone idea and garner the
industry and government support needed to turn the concept into a reality. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B>What&#146;s government&#146;s role? </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">For a large, ambitious project like this one to succeed, it will require the &#147;whole of government&#148; approach the Administration of U.S. President Joe
Biden has championed. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">New policies are needed to spur the investment required to deploy CCS on a pace and scale to meet Paris Agreement goals. Government
should establish a durable regulatory and legal environment and implement policies to enable CCS to receive direct investment and incentives. Establishing a market price on carbon will play an important part by providing the needed clarity and
stability required to drive investment. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B>Stay tuned: </B>Look out for more information on the Low Carbon Solutions business as its vision and strategy
takes shape.<B> </B> </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B>Important Additional Information Regarding Proxy Solicitation</B> </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B></B>Exxon Mobil Corporation (&#147;ExxonMobil&#148;) has filed a definitive proxy statement and form of associated BLUE proxy card with the U.S. Securities
and Exchange Commission (the &#147;SEC&#148;) in connection with the solicitation of proxies for ExxonMobil&#146;s 2021 Annual Meeting (the &#147;Proxy Statement&#148;). ExxonMobil, its directors and certain of its executive officers will be
participants in the solicitation of proxies from shareholders in respect of the 2021 Annual Meeting. Information regarding the names of ExxonMobil&#146;s directors and executive officers and their respective interests in ExxonMobil by security
holdings or otherwise is set forth in the Proxy Statement. To the extent holdings of such participants in ExxonMobil&#146;s securities are not reported, or have changed since the amounts described, in the Proxy Statement, such changes have been
reflected on Initial Statements of Beneficial Ownership on Form 3 or Statements of Change in Ownership on Form 4 filed with the SEC. Details concerning the nominees of ExxonMobil&#146;s Board of Directors for election at the 2021 Annual Meeting are
included in the Proxy Statement. BEFORE MAKING ANY VOTING DECISION, INVESTORS AND SHAREHOLDERS OF THE COMPANY ARE URGED TO READ ALL RELEVANT DOCUMENTS FILED WITH OR FURNISHED TO THE SEC, INCLUDING THE COMPANY&#146;S DEFINITIVE PROXY STATEMENT AND
ANY SUPPLEMENTS THERETO AND ACCOMPANYING BLUE PROXY CARD, BECAUSE THEY CONTAIN IMPORTANT INFORMATION. Investors and shareholders can obtain a copy of the Proxy Statement and other relevant documents filed by ExxonMobil free of charge from the
SEC&#146;s website, www.sec.gov. ExxonMobil&#146;s shareholders can also obtain, without charge, a copy of the Proxy Statement and other relevant filed documents by directing a request by mail to ExxonMobil Shareholder Services at 5959 Las Colinas
Boulevard, Irving, Texas, 75039-2298 or at shareholderrelations@exxonmobil.com or from the investor relations section of ExxonMobil&#146;s website, www.exxonmobil.com/investor. </P>

</DIV></Center>

<TD VALIGN="top"> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt; margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">&#147;&#133;America has a unique opportunity to spearhead a
breakthrough approach to reducing carbon emissions. As the world&#146;s leader in carbon capture and storage, ExxonMobil is eager to play our part&#133;&#148;</P> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt; margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Proxy Disclaimer:</P> <P STYLE="font-size:18pt; margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B>Important Additional Information Regarding Proxy Solicitation</B></P> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt; margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:1pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Exxon Mobil Corporation (&#147;ExxonMobil&#148;) has filed a definitive proxy statement and form of associated BLUE proxy card with the U.S. Securities and

<TD VALIGN="top"></TD>

<TD VALIGN="top"></TD></TR>
</TABLE>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center">6 </P>

</DIV></Center>


<p style="margin-top:1em; margin-bottom:0em; page-break-before:always">
<HR SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center"><B>ENERGY FACTOR DIGITAL CONTENT </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center"><B>PERSPECTIVES BLOG (energyfactor.com) </B></P> <P STYLE="font-size:12pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">


<IMG SRC="g177864g0420235640920.jpg" ALT="LOGO">
 </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B>Joe Blommaert </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B>04.20.21 </B></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B>The promise of carbon capture and storage,
and a <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">Texas-sized</FONT> call to action </B></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">ExxonMobil believes, and experts agree, that carbon capture and storage (CCS)
will need to play a critical role if the United States and other countries are to meet the emissions-reduction goals outlined in the Paris Agreement. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">CCS
could enable the United States to safely capture and store hundreds of millions of metric tons of carbon dioxide (CO2) each year that otherwise would be released into the atmosphere. It&#146;s one of the few proven technologies with the potential to
significantly lower emissions from certain <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">hard-to-decarbonize</FONT></FONT> sectors, such as manufacturing and heavy industry. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B>The question is: How can CCS be deployed broadly to help reduce U.S. emissions more quickly? </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">For the past three years, ExxonMobil has been assessing the concept of multi-user CCS &#147;hubs&#148; in industrial areas located near geologic storage sites,
such as depleted oil and gas reservoirs. We believe the time is right for a large-scale collaboration in the United States between government at every level, private industry, academia and local communities to create an &#147;Innovation Zone&#148;
approach to dramatically accelerate CCS progress. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B>And we think Houston is the perfect place for such a concept. </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Houston has two features that make it an ideal site for CCS: It has many large industrial emission sources, and it&#146;s located near geologic formations in
the Gulf of Mexico that could store large amounts of CO2 safely, securely and permanently. The U.S. Department of Energy estimates that storage capacity along the U.S. Gulf Coast is enough to hold 500&nbsp;billion metric tons of CO2 &#151; more than
130 years of the country&#146;s total industrial and power generation emissions, based on 2018 data. </P>
</DIV></Center>


<p style="margin-top:1em; margin-bottom:0em; page-break-before:always">
<HR SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">ExxonMobil believes the United States could establish a CCS Innovation Zone along the Houston Ship Channel
and surrounding industrial areas with the potential to effectively capture all the CO2 emissions from the petrochemical, manufacturing and power generation facilities located there. The CO2 would be piped into natural geologic formations thousands
of feet under the sea floor. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B>Big idea, big benefits </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">It would be a huge project, requiring the collective support of industry and government, with a combined estimated investment of $100&nbsp;billion or more.
</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">But the benefits could be equally big: Early projections indicate that if the appropriate policies were in place, infrastructure could be built in
Houston to safely capture and permanently store about 50&nbsp;million metric tons of CO2 annually by 2030. By 2040, it could be 100&nbsp;million metric tons. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">This concept could be a game-changer for deployment of CCS, benefitting not just Houston and its ambition to be carbon-neutral by 2050, but the United States
as a whole. In addition to having the potential to effectively decarbonize one of the country&#146;s largest sources of industrial emissions, the concept could generate tens of thousands of new jobs and protect thousands of existing jobs.
Importantly, CCS also promises the potential of significant impact at lower societal costs compared to other emissions reduction technologies, especially for the manufacturing sector. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Lessons learned from this Houston CCS Innovation Zone could be replicated in other areas of the country where there are similar concentrations of industrial
facilities located near suitable CO2 storage sites, such as in the Midwest or elsewhere along the U.S. Gulf Coast. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B>A collective effort, built on
Houston&#146;s history as an energy innovator </B></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">As the &#147;Energy Capital of the World&#148;, Houston is already the home to all kinds of energy
innovation. The Houston area also is home to more than 12,000 ExxonMobil employees, including myself. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">ExxonMobil is uniquely positioned to help advance
this Houston CCS Innovation Zone concept. We&#146;re the global leader in CCS, having cumulatively captured more anthropogenic CO2 around the world than anyone else. We also have extensive reservoir management expertise and decades of proven
performance in safely building and operating large-scale projects. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">But a concept as ambitious as a Houston CCS Innovation Zone will require a collective
effort. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">It will need collaboration among federal, state and local officials &#150; the &#147;whole of government&#148; approach the Biden Administration
has championed. It will need business support from across industries and community support. It will need government and private-sector funding, as well as enhanced regulatory and legal frameworks that enable investment and innovation. That&#146;s
why we envision a &#147;zone&#148; approach, similar to other public-private initiatives established to facilitate economic growth or tackle other broad societal challenges. </P>
</DIV></Center>


<p style="margin-top:1em; margin-bottom:0em; page-break-before:always">
<HR SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">And today, one of the biggest challenges is reducing the risks of climate change while continuing to meet
people&#146;s need for affordable energy and the products they rely on every day. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B>The role of policy </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">We applaud President Biden&#146;s decision to rejoin the Paris Agreement, a framework ExxonMobil has supported since its inception. We believe CCS should be a
key part of the U.S. strategy for meeting its Paris goals and included as part of the administration&#146;s upcoming Nationally Determined Contributions (NDC) submission. After all, the International Energy Agency has said, &#147;reaching <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">net-zero</FONT> [emissions] will be virtually impossible&#148; without CCS. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">New policies are needed, however, to spur the
investment required to deploy CCS on a pace and scale to meet Paris Agreement goals. Government should establish a durable regulatory and legal environment, and implement policies to enable CCS to receive direct investment and incentives similar to
those available to other efforts to reduce emissions. Establishing a market price on carbon will play an important part by providing the needed clarity and stability required to drive investment. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B>Looking ahead </B></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Meeting the goals of the Paris Agreement
is a big challenge &#150; requiring new technologies, new policies and new ways of thinking. A Houston CCS Innovation Zone could be a giant step in the right direction. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">In the weeks, months and years to come, ExxonMobil will continue to engage with the industry, government, academic and community leaders who will be needed to
make this concept a reality. I look forward to collaborating with them and helping reduce global CO2 emissions, starting right here in my adopted hometown of Houston. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><I>Joe Blommaert is president of ExxonMobil Low Carbon Solutions. </I></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><I>Click <U>HERE</U><U> </U>to learn more about ExxonMobil&#146;s work in carbon capture and storage. </I></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Statements of future events, conditions, plans, and objectives are forward looking statements. Actual future results, including plans and results of CCS
projects, societal emission reductions, the development of CCS business opportunities and markets, and the outcome of technology development projects could differ materially due to a number of factors. These include changes in law, taxes or
regulation, including environmental regulations; the ability to bring new technologies to commercial scale on a cost-competitive basis; development of policies and laws for carbon pricing and to support local, national and global markets for carbon
capture and storage; the timely granting of government permits; political sanctions and international treaties; unexpected technological developments; general economic conditions, including the occurrence and duration of economic recessions;
unforeseen technical or operating difficulties; and other factors discussed here, in Item 1A. Risk Factors in our Form <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">10-K</FONT> for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2020 and under the heading &#147;Factors
Affecting Future Results&#148; on the Investors page of our website at <U>www.exxonmobil.com</U><U> </U>under the heading News&nbsp;&amp; Resources. The forward-looking statements in this release are based on management&#146;s good faith estimates,
plans and objectives as of date of this release. We assume no duty to update these statements as of any future date. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center"><B>PERSPECTIVE BLOG

<p style="margin-top:1em; margin-bottom:0em; page-break-before:always">
<HR SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center"><B>ENERGY FACTOR SUBSCRIBER NEWSLETTER COPY </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">ExxonMobil believes the United States could establish a CCS Innovation Zone along the Houston Ship Channel and surrounding industrial areas with the potential
to effectively capture all the CO2 emissions from the petrochemical, manufacturing and power generation facilities located there. The CO2 would be piped into natural geologic formations thousands of feet under the sea floor. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Proxy Disclaimer: </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B>Important Additional Information
Regarding Proxy Solicitation </B></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Exxon Mobil Corporation (&#147;ExxonMobil&#148;) has filed a definitive proxy statement and form of associated BLUE proxy
card with the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission (the &#147;SEC&#148;) in connection with the solicitation of proxies for ExxonMobil&#146;s 2021 Annual Meeting (the &#147;Proxy Statement&#148;). ExxonMobil, its directors and certain of its
executive officers will be participants in the solicitation of proxies from shareholders in respect of the 2021 Annual Meeting. Information regarding the names of ExxonMobil&#146;s directors and executive officers and their respective interests in
ExxonMobil by security holdings or otherwise is set forth in the Proxy Statement. To the extent holdings of such participants in ExxonMobil&#146;s securities are not reported, or have changed since the amounts described, in the Proxy Statement, such
changes have been reflected on Initial Statements of Beneficial Ownership on Form 3 or Statements of Change in Ownership on Form 4 filed with the SEC. Details concerning the nominees of ExxonMobil&#146;s Board of Directors for election at the 2021
Annual Meeting are included in the Proxy Statement. BEFORE MAKING ANY VOTING DECISION, INVESTORS AND SHAREHOLDERS OF THE COMPANY ARE URGED TO READ ALL RELEVANT DOCUMENTS FILED WITH OR FURNISHED TO THE SEC, INCLUDING THE COMPANY&#146;S DEFINITIVE
PROXY STATEMENT AND ANY SUPPLEMENTS THERETO AND ACCOMPANYING BLUE PROXY CARD, BECAUSE THEY CONTAIN IMPORTANT INFORMATION. Investors and shareholders can obtain a copy of the Proxy Statement and other relevant documents filed by ExxonMobil free of
charge from the SEC&#146;s website, <U>www.sec.gov</U>. ExxonMobil&#146;s shareholders can also obtain, without charge, a copy of the Proxy Statement and other relevant filed documents by directing a request by mail to ExxonMobil Shareholder
Services at 5959 Las Colinas Boulevard, Irving, Texas, 75039-2298 or at <U>shareholderrelations@exxonmobil.com</U> or from the investor relations section of ExxonMobil&#146;s website, <U>www.exxonmobil.com/investor</U>. </P>

<TD VALIGN="top"> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Exciting news from <B>@Joe Blommaert</B>, the President of <B>@ExxonMobil</B> Low Carbon Solutions, our new business that&#146;s developing a
concept to decarbonize the industrial area in and surrounding the Houston Ship Channel with a large-scale carbon capture and storage (CCS) project. Houston is an ideal location for this important effort, one that is a critical piece in the fight
against climate change.</P> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt; margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Equally impressive is the impact a project of this size
could have on the greater Houston area. The proposed &#147;Houston Innovation Zone&#148; could protect current and generate thousands of new jobs, and reduce emissions at low to no cost. As the center of the O&amp;G industry in the U.S., Houston is
perfectly poised to serve as the site for this kind of transformative project. It&#146;s also a win for ExxonMobil&#146;s own talented people, from my colleagues <B>@Erik Oswald</B> and Joe Blommaert to the scores of researchers and scientists
working on both the capture and sequestration side of the technology.</P> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt; margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:1pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">This is a
great initiative that not only promotes an essential emissions-reducing technology but also positively impacts my city, Houston. I encourage you to read more from Joe: [LINK TO EF BLOG]</P></TD></TR>

<P STYLE="font-size:12pt; margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">[OMNIPRESENT] <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">-Joe</FONT> Blommaert, President of
ExxonMobil Low Carbon Solutions</P> <P STYLE="font-size:12pt; margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><I>&#147;We believe the time is right for an
&#147;Innovation Zone&#148; approach to dramatically accelerate carbon capture and storage progress. And we think Houston is the perfect place for such a concept.&#148;</I></P> <P STYLE="font-size:12pt; margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">LOGO</P> <P STYLE="font-size:12pt; margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Proxy disclaimer</P> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">

</P> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt; margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:1pt">&nbsp;</P></TD></TR>
</TABLE>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center">20 </P>

</DIV></Center>


<p style="margin-top:1em; margin-bottom:0em; page-break-before:always">
<HR SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">


<IMG SRC="g177864g0420235643556.jpg" ALT="LOGO">
 </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center"><B>ENERGY FACTOR DIGITAL CONTENT (energyfactor.com) </B></P>
<P STYLE="font-size:12pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt" ALIGN="center">


<IMG SRC="g177864page021b.jpg" ALT="LOGO">
 </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B>Charting a bold concept for a lower-carbon future </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B>04.21.21 </B></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">As the world marks Earth Day on April&nbsp;22,
government leaders from dozens of countries will meet at the virtual Leaders Summit on Climate that President Biden is convening. The conference will highlight the United States&#146; return to the Paris Agreement and seek to galvanize global
efforts to tackle climate change. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Charting a pathway to a lower-carbon future envisioned in the Paris Agreement requires bold thinking and large-scale
solutions where governments, academia and businesses work together. ExxonMobil, a supporter of the Paris Agreement <U>since its inception</U>, recently offered an approach focused on reducing CO2 emissions at unparalleled levels of scale and impact
from one of the busiest industrial corridors in the country. </P>
</DIV></Center>


<p style="margin-top:1em; margin-bottom:0em; page-break-before:always">
<HR SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B>A <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">Texas-sized</FONT> proposal for reducing carbon emissions </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Key themes of the <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">two-day</FONT> summit include spurring technologies that can help reduce emissions, while also creating
economic opportunities. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">For the past three years, ExxonMobil has been assessing the potential of carbon capture and storage (CCS) deployment in major
industrial &#147;hubs&#148; located near safe geological formations that can store CO2. One region emerged as a frontrunner: Houston. Home to the second-busiest port in the United States, Houston is ideally suited for building CCS infrastructure at
scale. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">That&#146;s why ExxonMobil&#146;s Low Carbon Solutions business has introduced the concept of a Houston Ship Channel CCS Innovation Zone, a bold
initiative to bring together governments, private sector and others to advance the policies and investments required for large-scale CCS deployment. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Fully developed, this concept has the potential to capture about 100&nbsp;million metric tons of CO2 emissions annually by 2040, effectively offsetting one of
the country&#146;s largest sources of industrial CO2 emissions. It could also protect and create thousands of jobs, while drastically accelerating U.S. emission-reduction efforts and providing substantial progress toward the country&#146;s
lower-carbon aspirations. For comparison, currently, the U.S. captures around 13&nbsp;million metric tons of CO2 emissions per year &#150; more than half of which is captured by ExxonMobil. </P>
<P STYLE="font-size:12pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt" ALIGN="center">


<IMG SRC="g177864g0420235644305.jpg" ALT="LOGO">
 </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Specifically, the collaborative effort would transport CO2 captured at industrial sites for safe and permanent storage in
dedicated <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">sub-surface</FONT> geologic formations deep under the Gulf of Mexico. According to the U.S. Department of Energy, the U.S. Gulf Coast has a projected capacity large enough to safely and permanently store
about 500&nbsp;billion metric tons of CO2. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B>&#147;A whole of government&#148; approach: </B>Given its proposed scale, the Houston Ship Channel CCS<B>
</B>Innovation Zone concept would require the support of multiple stakeholders, including academia, businesses and all levels of government. The concept could help accelerate funding from a variety of sources and facilitate the implementation of the
policy and regulatory landscape needed to jumpstart and sustain such an initiative. </P>
</DIV></Center>


<p style="margin-top:1em; margin-bottom:0em; page-break-before:always">
<HR SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">One such policy ExxonMobil has long encouraged <U>is a price on carbon emissions</U>. Establishing a market
price on carbon will play an important part by providing the needed clarity and stability required to drive investment. Government could also establish a durable regulatory and legal environment and implement policies to enable CCS to receive direct
investment and incentives similar to those available to other efforts to reduce emissions. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B>Why CCS?: </B>While technologies like wind and solar will
continue to play important roles in reducing<B> </B>emissions, CCS also offers a significant impact, particularly in the power generation and manufacturing sectors. As recently as last fall, the International Energy Agency said &#147;reaching <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">net-zero</FONT> [emissions] will be virtually impossible&#148; without it. President Biden has also talked about the importance of accelerating CCS growth as an approach that could benefit the economy and the environment.
</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">ExxonMobil&#146;s CCS portfolio also encompasses ongoing research work streams, including collaborations with five energy centers at leading research
universities and the U.S. National Labs. The company has more than 30 years of experience capturing carbon and owns about <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">one-fifth</FONT> of global CO2 capture capacity. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B>Why this matters: </B>The goals of the Paris Agreement cannot be achieved without reducing<B> </B>emissions across the power generation, industrial and
commercial transportation sectors. Power generation and heavy industry account for nearly 70&nbsp;percent of all global energy-related emissions, and CCS is one of the few proven technologies that could lower emissions in both of these sectors. The
prospect of bringing together public and private entities to collectively utilize CCS technology to significantly reduce the industrial emissions in a major U.S. city offers tremendous promise and opportunity. </P>
<P STYLE="font-size:12pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt" ALIGN="center">


<IMG SRC="g177864g0420235644508.jpg" ALT="LOGO">
 </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The Houston Ship Channel CCS Innovation Zone concept would be an ambitious undertaking. Its success could provide a
potential blueprint to help decarbonize other high-emission areas in the United States and could become a significant component of the country&#146;s overall contribution toward the goal of a lower-carbon energy future. </P>
</DIV></Center>


<p style="margin-top:1em; margin-bottom:0em; page-break-before:always">
<HR SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Statements of future events, conditions, plans, and objectives are forward looking statements. Actual future
results, including plans and results of CCS projects, societal emission reductions, the development of CCS business opportunities and markets, and the outcome of technology development projects could differ materially due to a number of factors.
These include changes in law, taxes or regulation, including environmental regulations; the ability to bring new technologies to commercial scale on a cost-competitive basis; development of policies and laws for carbon pricing and to support local,
national and global markets for carbon capture and storage; the timely granting of government permits; political sanctions and international treaties; unexpected technological developments; general economic conditions, including the occurrence and
duration of economic recessions; unforeseen technical or operating difficulties; and other factors discussed here, in Item 1A. Risk Factors in our Form <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">10-K</FONT> for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2020 and under
the heading &#147;Factors Affecting Future Results&#148; on the Investors page of our website at <U>www.exxonmobil.com</U> under the heading News&nbsp;&amp; Resources. The forward-looking statements in this release are based on management&#146;s
good faith estimates, plans and objectives as of date of this release. We assume no duty to update these statements as of any future date. </P> <P STYLE="font-size:18pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">


<IMG SRC="g177864g0420235645569.jpg" ALT="LOGO">
 </P> <P STYLE="font-size:18pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">

<IMG SRC="g177864g0420235645803.jpg" ALT="LOGO">
 </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center"><B>ENERGY FACTOR SUBSCRIBER NEWSLETTERCOPY </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:4%; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">ExxonMobil&#146;s new Low Carbon Solutions business is proposing a concept to help accelerate emissions-reductions from a heavy industrial
area around the Houston Ship Channel with large-scale carbon capture and storage. Find out more about this concept and why it matters. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:4%; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Proxy Disclaimer: </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:4%; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B>Important
Additional Information Regarding Proxy Solicitation </B></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:4%; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Exxon Mobil Corporation (&#147;ExxonMobil&#148;) has filed a definitive proxy
statement and form of associated BLUE proxy card with the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission (the &#147;SEC&#148;) in connection with the solicitation of proxies for ExxonMobil&#146;s 2021 Annual Meeting (the &#147;Proxy Statement&#148;).
ExxonMobil, its directors and certain of its executive officers will be participants in the solicitation of proxies from shareholders in respect of the 2021 Annual Meeting. Information regarding the names of ExxonMobil&#146;s directors and executive
officers and their respective interests in ExxonMobil by security holdings or otherwise is set forth in the Proxy Statement. To the extent holdings of such participants in ExxonMobil&#146;s securities are not reported, or have changed since the
amounts described, in the Proxy Statement, such changes have been reflected on Initial Statements of Beneficial Ownership on Form 3 or Statements of Change in Ownership on Form 4 filed with the SEC. Details concerning the nominees of
ExxonMobil&#146;s Board of Directors for election at the 2021 Annual Meeting are included in the Proxy Statement. BEFORE MAKING ANY VOTING DECISION, INVESTORS AND SHAREHOLDERS OF THE COMPANY ARE URGED TO READ ALL RELEVANT DOCUMENTS FILED WITH OR
FURNISHED TO THE SEC, INCLUDING THE COMPANY&#146;S DEFINITIVE PROXY STATEMENT AND ANY SUPPLEMENTS THERETO AND ACCOMPANYING BLUE PROXY CARD, BECAUSE THEY CONTAIN IMPORTANT INFORMATION. Investors and shareholders can obtain a copy of the Proxy
Statement and other relevant documents filed by ExxonMobil free of charge from the SEC&#146;s website, <U>www.sec.gov</U><U>.</U> ExxonMobil&#146;s shareholders can also obtain, without charge, a copy of the Proxy Statement and other relevant filed
documents by directing a request by mail to ExxonMobil Shareholder Services at 5959 Las Colinas Boulevard, Irving, Texas, 75039-2298 or at <U>shareholderrelations@exxonmobil.com</U> or from the investor relations section of ExxonMobil&#146;s

<TD VALIGN="top">could remove as much as 100M tons of carbon annually by 2040</TD></TR>

</P> <P STYLE="font-size:12pt; margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B>A bold plan to capture and store CO<SUB
STYLE="font-size:85%; vertical-align:bottom">2</SUB></B></P> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt; margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:1pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">When it comes to helping
the U.S. meet its emissions-reduction goals, ExxonMobil is thinking big. That&#146;s why it&#146;s proposing an ambitious carbon capture and storage concept that has the potential to capture 100&nbsp;million metric tons of CO<SUB
STYLE="font-size:85%; vertical-align:bottom">2</SUB> annually by 2040. This CCS hub along the Houston Ship Channel, one of the most active U.S. industrial corridors, has the potential to capture effectively all the emissions from local
petrochemical, manufacturing and power generation facilities located there and store them in geologic formations underneath the Gulf of Mexico</P></TD></TR>

potential of the Houston CCS concept. <B></B></P> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt; margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

participants in the solicitation of proxies from shareholders in respect of the 2021 Annual Meeting. Information regarding the names of ExxonMobil&#146;s directors and executive officers and their respective interests in ExxonMobil by security
holdings or otherwise is set forth in the Proxy Statement. To the extent holdings of such participants in ExxonMobil&#146;s securities are not reported, or have changed since the amounts described, in the Proxy Statement, such changes have been
reflected on Initial Statements of Beneficial Ownership on Form 3 or Statements of Change in </P>

INCLUDING THE COMPANY&#146;S DEFINITIVE PROXY STATEMENT AND ANY SUPPLEMENTS THERETO AND ACCOMPANYING BLUE PROXY CARD, BECAUSE THEY CONTAIN IMPORTANT INFORMATION. Investors and shareholders can obtain a copy of the Proxy Statement and other relevant
documents filed by ExxonMobil free of charge from the SEC&#146;s website, <U>www.sec.gov</U>. ExxonMobil&#146;s shareholders can also obtain, without charge, a copy of the Proxy Statement and other relevant filed documents by directing a request by
mail to ExxonMobil Shareholder Services at 5959 Las Colinas Boulevard, Irving, Texas, 75039-2298 or at <U>shareholderrelations@exxonmobil.com</U> or from the investor relations section of ExxonMobil&#146;s website,

<p style="margin-top:1em; margin-bottom:0em; page-break-before:always">
<HR SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt" ALIGN="right">


<IMG SRC="g177864g0421000132696.jpg" ALT="LOGO">
 </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B>Carbon Capture and Storage (CCS) </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B>Houston Ship Channel CCS Hub concept </B></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B>What is carbon
capture and storage (CCS)? </B></P> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="1%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left" STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt">CCS is the process of capturing carbon dioxide (CO2) emissions that would otherwise be released into the
atmosphere and storing them safely and permanently in underground geologic formations. </P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="1%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left" STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt">The International Energy Agency and others agree that a broad deployment of CCS will be needed to meet the Paris
Agreement&#146;s goals, because CCS is one of the few proven technologies with the potential to significantly reduce emissions from <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">hard-to-decarbonize</FONT></FONT> sectors, such as
manufacturing and heavy industry. </P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="1%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left" STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt">The International Energy Agency has said, &#147;reaching <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">net-zero</FONT>
[emissions] will be virtually impossible&#148; without CCS. </P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B>What is ExxonMobil&#146;s new CCS concept? </B></P>
<P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="1%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left" STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt">For the past three years, ExxonMobil has been assessing the concept of multi-user CCS &#147;hubs&#148; in
industrial areas located near geologic formations that could be used to safely, securely and permanently store CO2. </P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="1%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left" STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt">We believe the time is right for a large-scale collaboration in the U.S. between governments at every level,
private industry, academia and local communities to create an &#147;Innovation Zone&#148; approach that could facilitate the creation of such hubs. </P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="1%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left" STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt">A CCS Innovation Zone could bring together government incentives and private-sector investment, along with new
policies and regulations to encourage deployment; enable the safe collection, storage and transport of the CO2; and secure vital community support. </P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="1%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left" STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt">We believe the U.S. could establish a CCS Innovation Zone along the Houston Ship Channel and surrounding
industrial areas. </P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B>Why Houston? </B></P> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="1%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left" STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt">Houston is an ideal location for large-scale CCS: It has many industrial emission sources, and it&#146;s near
geologic formations in the Gulf of Mexico that could store large amounts of CO2 safely, securely and permanently. The U.S. Department of Energy estimates that storage capacity along the U.S. Gulf Coast is about 500&nbsp;billion metric tons of CO2
&#150; more than 130 years of the country&#146;s total industrial and power generation emissions, based on 2018 data. </P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B>How much CO2
could this Houston CCS concept save? </B></P> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="1%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left" STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt">Early projections indicate if the appropriate policies were in place, infrastructure could be built in Houston to
safely capture and permanently store about 50&nbsp;million metric tons of CO2 annually by 2030 and 100&nbsp;million metric tons by 2040 &#150; effectively all the CO2 emissions from the petrochemical, manufacturing and electricity generation
facilities in that area. </P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="1%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left" STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt">Capturing 100&nbsp;million metric tons of CO2 is equal to taking 20&nbsp;million cars off the road (1/12 of the
U.S. fleet). It is also equal to the CO2 sequestered by about 120&nbsp;million acres of forest &#150; an area larger than the state of California. </P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="1%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left" STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt">Collectively, the world has captured nearly 300&nbsp;million metric tons of CO2 over the past 50 years. This
Houston CCS concept has the potential to capture a third of that amount every year by 2040. </P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:4%; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="right"><I>(continues) </I></P>
</DIV></Center>


<p style="margin-top:1em; margin-bottom:0em; page-break-before:always">
<HR SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B>Are there other benefits besides emissions-reduction? </B></P>
<P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="1%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left" STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt">In addition to having the potential to effectively decarbonize one of the country&#146;s largest sources of
industrial emissions, the creation of a Houston CCS hub could generate tens of thousands of new U.S. jobs and protect thousands of existing jobs. </P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="1%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left" STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt">It could also help Houston meet its ambition to be carbon-neutral by 2050. Lessons learned could be replicated in
other areas of the U.S. where there are similar concentrations of industrial facilities located near suitable CO2 storage sites, such as in the Midwest or elsewhere along the U.S. Gulf Coast. </P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B>What would it cost? </B></P> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="1%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left" STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt">The concept would require the collective support of industry and government, with a combined estimated investment
of $100&nbsp;billion or more. </P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="1%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left" STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt">CCS also has potential to reduce emissions at a lower societal cost compared to other technologies, especially in
the manufacturing sector. </P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B>What is ExxonMobil&#146;s role? </B></P>
<P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="1%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left" STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt">ExxonMobil is well suited and eager to play our part in the collaborative effort to advance this challenging,
complex concept, in collaboration with other industry participants, governments, academia and others. </P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="1%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left" STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt">ExxonMobil is the global leader in CCS, having cumulatively captured more anthropogenic CO2 around the world than
anyone else, and we are assessing several other CCS opportunities. We also have extensive reservoir management expertise and decades of proven performance in safely building and operating large-scale projects. </P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B>What is government&#146;s role? </B></P> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="1%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left" STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt">We applaud President Biden&#146;s decision to rejoin the Paris Agreement, a framework ExxonMobil has supported
since its inception. We believe CCS should be a key part of the U.S. strategy for meeting its emissions goals. </P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="1%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left" STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt">Widespread deployment of CCS technology at a commercial scale will require sufficient government support,
including financial incentives and a policy and regulatory framework that would: </P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="5%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left" STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt">Allow CO2 captured from any source to be stored offshore; </P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="5%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left" STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt">Include a mechanism to <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">de-risk</FONT> the long-term liability obligations for
stored CO2; </P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="5%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left" STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt">Provide reasonable standards to ensure safe, reliable and permanent CO2 storage; </P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="5%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left" STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt">Allow for <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">fit-for-purpose</FONT></FONT> CO2
injection well-design standards; </P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="5%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left" STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt">Provide legal certainty for pore space ownership; </P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="5%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left" STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt">Ensure a streamlined permitting process for CCS facilities; and </P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="5%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left" STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt">Provide access to CO2 storage capacity owned or controlled by governments. </P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="1%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left" STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt">ExxonMobil supports policies that provide a predictable price on carbon emissions, which would enable companies
to evaluate the long-term commercial viability of new or expanded CCS investments. </P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B>Is CCS safe? </B></P>
<P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="1%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left" STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt">Decades of research confirms the U.S. Gulf Coast is a safe place to store CO2. </P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="1%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left" STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt">The CO2 this Houston CCS concept could capture would be stored offshore thousands of feet below the seabed; a
thick layer of seal rock would prevent CO2 from escaping. </P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="1%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left" STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt">ExxonMobil has decades of experience in the safe operation of world-scale projects. Cutting-edge technologies
would be used to design safe CO2 storage projects and take corrective actions if needed. </P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:4%; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="right"><I>(continues)
</I></P>
</DIV></Center>

<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B>Important Additional Information Regarding Proxy Solicitation </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Exxon Mobil Corporation (&#147;ExxonMobil&#148;) has filed a definitive proxy statement and form of associated BLUE proxy card with the U.S. Securities and
Exchange Commission (the &#147;SEC&#148;) in connection with the solicitation of proxies for ExxonMobil&#146;s 2021 Annual Meeting (the &#147;Proxy Statement&#148;). ExxonMobil, its directors and certain of its executive officers will be
participants in the solicitation of proxies from shareholders in respect of the 2021 Annual Meeting. Information regarding the names of ExxonMobil&#146;s directors and executive officers and their respective interests in ExxonMobil by security
holdings or otherwise is set forth in the Proxy Statement. To the extent holdings of such participants in ExxonMobil&#146;s securities are not reported, or have changed since the amounts described, in the Proxy Statement, such changes have been
reflected on Initial Statements of Beneficial Ownership on Form 3 or Statements of Change in Ownership on Form 4 filed with the SEC. Details concerning the nominees of ExxonMobil&#146;s Board of Directors for election at the 2021 Annual Meeting are
included in the Proxy Statement. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">BEFORE MAKING ANY VOTING DECISION, INVESTORS AND SHAREHOLDERS OF THE COMPANY ARE URGED TO READ ALL RELEVANT DOCUMENTS
FILED WITH OR FURNISHED TO THE SEC, INCLUDING THE COMPANY&#146;S DEFINITIVE PROXY STATEMENT AND ANY SUPPLEMENTS THERETO AND ACCOMPANYING BLUE PROXY CARD, BECAUSE THEY CONTAIN IMPORTANT INFORMATION. Investors and shareholders can obtain a copy of the
Proxy Statement and other relevant documents filed by ExxonMobil free of charge from the SEC&#146;s website, <U>www.sec.gov</U>. ExxonMobil&#146;s shareholders can also obtain, without charge, a copy of the Proxy Statement and other relevant filed
documents by directing a request by mail to ExxonMobil Shareholder Services at 5959 Las Colinas Boulevard, Irving, Texas, 75039-2298 or at <U>shareholderrelations@exxonmobil.com</U> or from the investor relations section of ExxonMobil&#146;s
website, <U>www.exxonmobil.com/investor</U>. </P>
